        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "I was digging into this a bit and noticed an interesting stuff\n\nWhen using `silent!`, it suppresses the output for in process Lua callbacks (like `on_lines`), which makes sense since valid print output is silenced. However, it seems that remote plugins (RPC listeners) attached to the same buffer are *not* affected by this, they still receive the events and can print/log freely\n\nI am curious if this difference is intended? I see that buf_updates_send_changes in buffer_updates.c handles both RPC and Lua listeners, but the Lua ones seem to inherit the global `msg_silent` state, therefore \"by accident\" silencing them compared to RPC counterparts",
